    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> I think it's better because it allows you to add different hooks from different places, and setting a hook by using events means you're not replacing someone else's hook!\n\nAgree that for events it's always better to use a real event interface. But here I wonder, it's really a hook. Something that will completely replace the helper.search() calls by anything you do.\n\nIn the end I guess you are both right @bobylito @olance, making it an event will make it more flexible and also more inline with what we have today (other events)\n\nMaybe we should split it in two,\n\nAdd a `beforeSearch` event:\n\n``` js\nsearch.on('beforeSearch', function(helper) {\n  // do anything you want with the helper\n  // no need to call helper.search()\n});\n```\n\nSolves adding filters programmatically.\n\nAdd a `searchFunction` API entry, it will default to helper.search()\n\n``` js\ninstantsearch(appID, apiKey, {\n  searchFunction: function(helper) {\n    // your responsibility to call helper.search()\n   }\n});\n```\n\nSolves other cases like min char length, debounce ..\n\nI am proposing this split because I read\n\n> I think it's better because it allows you to add different hooks from different places\n\nAnd yes it makes sense but only if it's not actually your responsibility to call helper.search when using the event, otherwise you would have to synchronize yourself between your event listeners for who should call helper.search().\n\n@bobylito \n\n> And like DOM events, provide a function that would let stop the behavior?\n\nIf we do this, it would be harder for consumers to then implement debouncing. Since you would have to somehow still call a method to say \"do not search\".\n",
