  {
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> Well having configuration for hooks in multiple places might lead to poorly understandable behavior. For example if you have two hooks set in different places you won't necessarily know exactly what the other one is doing. If both try to do the same thing (like a debounce) it can be pretty messy.\n\nI agree, but that's something you should leave to the developer.\nI have had problems with that kind of decisions being made for me in the past. Forcing a single hook can be in some situations very difficult to work with. When several event hooks can be registered, you have more flexibility and you can decide what's OK to do and what's not depending on your own context.\n\nI am not sure I agree with the complexity of having two methods introduced.  \nI see this `beforeSearch` hook just as a \"before filter\" in Rails: you can register several filters that will be called one after the other before a controller action takes place; any of the filters can return false/raise an exception/trigger a redirect, which will block the default execution flow.\n\nAn analogy that could make more sense here are the middlewares in Express.js for instance.  \nWhy should we separate this logic into two different methods/hooks when you can have a single one?\n\nCall the hooks in the order they were registered. Each hook can change the helper config and do just that, and others can prevent search execution by returning false or calling a special function (I'd prefer returning false but that's another point).  \nI can't see the need for a special function that would replace the search logic?\n",
